(32, 'Mastering Candlestick Patterns: A Comprehensive Guide to Identifying and Interpreting All Major Patterns in Technical Analysis', 23, 38, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;Mastering Candlestick Patterns<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Introduction to Candlestick Charts<o:p></o:p></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\">Overview of the history and\r\nevolution of candlestick charts<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\">Understanding the anatomy of a\r\ncandlestick (including the body, wick, and shadow)<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\">Importance of candlestick charts in\r\ntechnical analysis<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>&nbsp;Basic Candlestick\r\nPatterns<o:p></o:p></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><b>Bullish engulfing\r\npatterns</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" data-filename=\"Web capture_21-2-2023_8428_www.bing.com.jpeg\" style=\"width: 484px;\"><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><o:p><br></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Bullish and bearish engulfing patterns are two commonly used\r\ncandlestick patterns in technical analysis. These patterns can be used to\r\nidentify potential trend reversals in the market.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">A bullish engulfing pattern occurs when a small bearish\r\ncandle is followed by a larger bullish candle, with the bullish candle\r\ncompletely engulfing the previous bearish candle. This pattern suggests that\r\nthe buyers have taken control of the market and may continue to push prices\r\nhigher. Traders often look for this pattern after a prolonged downtrend, as it\r\ncan signal a potential reversal. A picture of a bullish engulfing pattern can\r\nbe found on most charting software or online, and it is often accompanied by a\r\ndescription or explanation of what the pattern represents.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left: 0.5in;\"><b>Bearish engulfing patterns</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left: 0.5in;\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" data-filename=\"Web capture_21-2-2023_8135_www.bing.com.jpeg\" style=\"width: 520px;\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">On the other hand, a bearish engulfing pattern occurs when a\r\nsmall bullish candle is followed by a larger bearish candle, with the bearish\r\ncandle completely engulfing the previous bullish candle. This pattern suggests\r\nthat the sellers have taken control of the market and may continue to push\r\nprices lower. Traders often look for this pattern after a prolonged uptrend, as\r\nit can signal a potential reversal. A picture of a bearish engulfing pattern\r\ncan also be found on most charting software or online, and it is often\r\naccompanied by a description or explanation of what the pattern represents.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">In summary, both bullish and bearish engulfing patterns can\r\nbe used to identify potential trend reversals in the market. These patterns are\r\noften accompanied by pictures and descriptions that can be found on most\r\ncharting software or online. Traders use these patterns in conjunction with\r\nother technical indicators and fundamental analysis to make informed trading\r\ndecisions.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Varela Round&quot;; font-size: 10.5pt;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Hammer and hanging man&nbsp;</span><font face=\"Varela Round\">patterns.</font></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" data-filename=\"Web capture_21-2-2023_897_www.bing.com.jpeg\" style=\"width: 25%;\"><b><font face=\"Varela Round\"><br></font></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><o:p><br></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">In candlestick charts, the colors red and green are often\r\nused to represent bearish and bullish price movements, respectively. A hammer\r\npattern appears as a small candlestick with a long lower shadow and a small\r\nreal body near the top of the candle, and it is typically colored green to\r\nrepresent the bullish sentiment. This pattern suggests that the sellers pushed\r\nthe price down during the day, but the buyers were able to push the price back\r\nup and close near the opening price, indicating potential bullish reversal,\r\nespecially after a prolonged downtrend.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">On the other hand, a <b>hanging man</b> pattern is essentially a\r\nbearish version of the hammer pattern. It occurs when a small candlestick has a\r\nlong lower shadow and a small real body near the top of the candle, and it is\r\ntypically colored red to represent the bearish sentiment. This pattern suggests\r\nthat the buyers tried to push the price higher, but the sellers were able to\r\npush the price down and close near the opening price, indicating potential\r\nbearish reversal, especially after a prolonged uptrend.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">In summary, both hammer and <b>hanging man</b> patterns can be used\r\nto identify potential trend reversals in the market, and their colors are\r\ntypically green and red, respectively, to represent bullish and bearish\r\nsentiment. These patterns can be identified by their distinctive shapes and\r\ncolors, and they are often accompanied by pictures and descriptions that can be\r\nfound on most charting software or online. Traders use these patterns in\r\nconjunction with other technical indicators and fundamental analysis to make\r\ninformed trading decisions.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><b>Inverted hammer and shooting star\r\npatterns</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" data-filename=\"Web capture_21-2-2023_81717_www.bing.com.jpeg\" style=\"width: 481px;\"><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">An <b>inverted hammer </b>pattern is a bullish reversal pattern\r\nthat occurs when a small candle has a long upper shadow and a small real body\r\nnear the bottom of the candle. This pattern suggests that the sellers were in\r\ncontrol during the day, pushing the price down, but buyers were able to push\r\nthe price back up and close near the opening price. This pattern indicates\r\npotential bullish reversal, especially when it occurs after a prolonged\r\ndowntrend.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">On the other hand, a <b>shooting star</b> pattern is essentially a\r\nbearish version of the inverted hammer pattern. It occurs when a small candle\r\nhas a long upper shadow and a small real body near the bottom of the candle,\r\nbut it appears at the top of an uptrend. This pattern suggests that the buyers\r\ntried to push the price higher, but the sellers were able to push the price\r\ndown and close near the opening price. This pattern indicates potential bearish\r\nreversal, especially when it occurs after a prolonged uptrend.)</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Reversal Candlestick Patterns<o:p></o:p></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\">Morning and evening star patterns</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" data-filename=\"Web capture_21-2-2023_82035_www.bing.com.jpeg\" style=\"width: 498px;\"><o:p><br></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><o:p><br></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">A <b>morning star</b> pattern occurs during a downtrend and\r\nconsists of three candles. The first candle is a long bearish candle, which is\r\nfollowed by a short candle with a small real body. The third candle is a long\r\nbullish candle that closes well above the midpoint of the first candle. This\r\npattern suggests that the sellers were in control during the first day, but on\r\nthe second day, there was indecision in the market. On the third day, buyers\r\ntook control and pushed the price up, potentially indicating a bullish\r\nreversal.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><o:p>\r\n\r\n</o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">An <b>evening star</b> pattern is essentially the bearish version\r\nof the morning star pattern. It occurs during an uptrend and consists of three\r\ncandles. The first candle is a long bullish candle, which is followed by a\r\nshort candle with a small real body. The third candle is a long bearish candle\r\nthat closes well below the midpoint of the first candle. This pattern suggests\r\nthat the buyers were in control during the first day, but on the second day,\r\nthere was indecision in the market. On the third day, sellers took control and\r\npushed the price down, potentially indicating a bearish reversal.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><b>Three white soldiers and three\r\nblack crows patterns</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" data-filename=\"Web capture_21-2-2023_82734_www.bing.com.jpeg\" style=\"width: 672px;\"><b><br></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Three white soldiers</b> is a bullish pattern that occurs during\r\na downtrend. It is formed by three consecutive long green candles, each of\r\nwhich closes higher than the previous days close. This pattern suggests that\r\nthe buyers have taken control of the market and are pushing the price up,\r\npotentially indicating a bullish reversal.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">On the other hand,<b style=\"\"> three black crows</b> is a bearish pattern\r\nthat occurs during an uptrend. It is formed by three consecutive long red\r\ncandles, each of which closes lower than the previous days close. This pattern\r\nsuggests that the sellers have taken control of the market and are pushing the\r\nprice down, potentially indicating a bearish reversal.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Both patterns can be identified by their distinctive shapes,\r\nand they are often accompanied by pictures and descriptions that can be found\r\non most charting software or online. Traders use these patterns in conjunction\r\nwith other technical indicators and fundamental analysis to make informed\r\ntrading decisions.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p>Bullish and bearish harami patterns</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" data-filename=\"Web capture_21-2-2023_8312_www.bing.com.jpeg\" style=\"width: 470px;\"><b><br></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">A <b>bullish harami</b> pattern occurs during a downtrend and\r\nconsists of two candles. The first candle is a long bearish candle, followed by\r\na short candle with a small real body that is completely engulfed by the real\r\nbody of the first candle. This pattern suggests that the sellers were in\r\ncontrol during the first day, but on the second day, there was indecision in\r\nthe market and the buyers were able to push the price up. This potential\r\nreversal in momentum is often seen as a signal for a bullish reversal.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">A <b>bearish harami</b> pattern is essentially the opposite of the\r\nbullish harami pattern. It occurs during an uptrend and consists of two\r\ncandles. The first candle is a long bullish candle, followed by a short candle\r\nwith a small real body that is completely engulfed by the real body of the\r\nfirst candle. This pattern suggests that the buyers were in control during the first\r\nday, but on the second day, there was indecision in the market and the sellers\r\nwere able to push the price down. This potential reversal in momentum is often\r\nseen as a signal for a bearish reversal.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Both patterns can be identified by their distinctive shapes\r\nand are often accompanied by pictures and descriptions that can be found on\r\nmost charting software or online. Traders use these patterns in conjunction\r\nwith other technical indicators and fundamental analysis to make informed\r\ntrading decisions.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><b>Tweezer top and bottom patterns</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" data-filename=\"Web capture_21-2-2023_83635_www.bing.com.jpeg\" style=\"width: 242px;\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">A <b>tweezer top </b>pattern occurs during an uptrend and is formed\r\nby two candles with equal or almost equal highs, forming a resistance level.\r\nThe first candle is a long green candle, followed by a long red candle with the\r\nsame high or almost the same high as the previous candle. This pattern suggests\r\nthat the buyers were in control during the first day, but on the second day,\r\nthe sellers were able to push the price down and match the high of the previous\r\ndays candle, potentially indicating a bearish reversal.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">A <b>tweezer bottom</b> pattern occurs during a downtrend and is\r\nformed by two candles with equal or almost equal lows, forming a support level.\r\nThe first candle is a long red candle, followed by a long green candle with the\r\nsame low or almost the same low as the previous candle. This pattern suggests\r\nthat the sellers were in control during the first day, but on the second day,\r\nthe buyers were able to push the price up and match the low of the previous days\r\ncandle, potentially indicating a bullish reversal.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Both patterns can be identified by their distinctive shapes\r\nand are often accompanied by pictures and descriptions that can be found on\r\nmost charting software or online. Traders use these patterns in conjunction\r\nwith other technical indicators and fundamental analysis to make informed\r\ntrading decisions.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Continuation Candlestick Patterns<o:p></o:p></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><b>Rising and falling three methods\r\npatterns</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" data-filename=\"Web capture_21-2-2023_84042_www.bing.com.jpeg\" style=\"width: 501px;\"><b><br></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The<b> rising three </b>methods pattern occurs during an uptrend\r\nand is made up of a long green candlestick, followed by three or more small red\r\ncandles, and then closed by another long green candlestick. The small red\r\ncandles are typically contained within the range of the first long green\r\ncandle. This pattern suggests that the market is taking a brief pause from the\r\nuptrend, consolidating its gains, before continuing in the same upward\r\ndirection. It can indicate a bullish continuation pattern.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The <b>falling three </b>methods pattern is the opposite of the\r\nrising three methods pattern, and it occurs during a downtrend. It is made up\r\nof a long red candlestick, followed by three or more small green candles, and\r\nthen closed by another long red candlestick. The small green candles are\r\ntypically contained within the range of the first long red candle. This pattern\r\nsuggests that the market is taking a brief pause from the downtrend,\r\nconsolidating its losses, before continuing in the same downward direction. It\r\ncan indicate a bearish continuation pattern.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Both patterns can be identified by their distinctive shapes\r\nand are often accompanied by pictures and descriptions that can be found on\r\nmost charting software or online. Traders use these patterns in conjunction\r\nwith other technical indicators and fundamental analysis to make informed\r\ntrading decisions.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><b>Bullish and bearish flag patterns</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" data-filename=\"Web capture_21-2-2023_84759_www.bing.com.jpeg\" style=\"width: 589px;\"><b><br></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><b><br></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The <b>bullish flag </b>pattern typically occurs during an uptrend\r\nand is characterized by a sharp upward move (the flagpole) followed by a period\r\nof consolidation in a downward sloping channel (the flag). The flag is\r\ntypically formed by a series of lower highs and lower lows, indicating that\r\ntraders are taking a pause from buying, but are not aggressively selling. The\r\npattern is completed when the price breaks out of the flag to the upside, indicating\r\na continuation of the uptrend. This pattern can be a bullish continuation\r\npattern.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The <b>bearish flag</b> pattern is the opposite of the bullish flag\r\npattern and typically occurs during a downtrend. It is characterized by a sharp\r\ndownward move (the flagpole) followed by a period of consolidation in an upward\r\nsloping channel (the flag). The flag is typically formed by a series of higher\r\nlows and lower highs, indicating that traders are taking a pause from selling,\r\nbut are not aggressively buying. The pattern is completed when the price breaks\r\nout of the flag to the downside, indicating a continuation of the downtrend.\r\nThis pattern can be a bearish continuation pattern.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Both patterns can be identified by their distinctive shapes\r\nand are often accompanied by pictures and descriptions that can be found on\r\nmost charting software or online. Traders use these patterns in conjunction\r\nwith other technical indicators and fundamental analysis to make informed\r\ntrading decisions.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><b>Bullish and bearish pennant\r\npatterns</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" data-filename=\"Web capture_21-2-2023_84817_www.bing.com.jpeg\" style=\"width: 569px;\"><b><br></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><b><br></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The <b>bullish pennant</b> pattern occurs during an uptrend and is\r\ncharacterized by a small symmetrical triangle (the pennant) that forms after a\r\nsharp upward move. The pennant is typically formed by two converging trend\r\nlines, with the upper trend line acting as resistance and the lower trend line\r\nacting as support. The pattern is completed when the price breaks out of the\r\npennant to the upside, indicating a continuation of the uptrend.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The <b>bearish pennant</b> pattern is the opposite of the bullish\r\npennant pattern and typically occurs during a downtrend. It is characterized by\r\na small symmetrical triangle (the pennant) that forms after a sharp downward\r\nmove. The pennant is typically formed by two converging trend lines, with the\r\nlower trend line acting as resistance and the upper trend line acting as support.\r\nThe pattern is completed when the price breaks out of the pennant to the\r\ndownside, indicating a continuation of the downtrend.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Both patterns can be identified by their distinctive shapes\r\nand are often accompanied by pictures and descriptions that can be found on\r\nmost charting software or online. Traders use these patterns in conjunction\r\nwith other technical indicators and fundamental analysis to make informed\r\ntrading decisions.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Application of Candlestick Pattern</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Identifying and interpreting\r\ncandlestick patterns in different market environments</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">In an <b>uptrend</b>, traders will typically look for bullish\r\ncandlestick patterns, such as hammer, morning star, and three white soldiers,\r\nto indicate potential continuation of the trend. On the other hand, bearish\r\ncandlestick patterns, such as shooting star, evening star, and three black\r\ncrows, may indicate a potential reversal of the trend.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">In a <b>downtrend</b>, traders will typically look for bearish\r\ncandlestick patterns, such as hanging man, dark cloud cover, and three black\r\ncrows, to indicate potential continuation of the trend. Bullish candlestick\r\npatterns, such as hammer, morning star, and three white soldiers, may indicate\r\na potential reversal of the trend.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">In a <b>sideways or range-bound </b>market, traders may look for\r\npatterns such as doji, spinning top, and tweezer tops and bottoms to indicate\r\nindecision in the market and a potential shift in direction.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">It is important to note that these candlestick patterns\r\nshould not be used in isolation and should always be considered within the\r\nbroader context of market trends and other technical indicators to confirm\r\npotential trend reversals or continuations. Additionally, it is always\r\nimportant to remember that technical analysis is not foolproof, and patterns\r\nmay not always accurately predict future market movements.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Varela Round&quot;; font-size: 10.5pt;\"><b>Using candlestick patterns in trade\r\nentry and exit strategies.</b></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Candlestick patterns are a popular tool used by traders to\r\nidentify potential market reversals and entry and exit points for trades. Here\r\nis an example of how a trader might use candlestick patterns in their trade\r\nentry and exit strategies:<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Suppose a trader is analyzing a chart for a particular\r\nasset, such as a stock or cryptocurrency, and they notice a bullish reversal\r\npattern forming. A bullish reversal pattern is a candlestick pattern that\r\nsuggests a potential reversal from a downtrend to an uptrend.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The trader sees that the asset has been in a downtrend for\r\nthe past few weeks, but the latest candlestick on the chart is a\r\n\"hammer\" pattern. A hammer pattern has a small body and a long lower\r\nwick, with little to no upper wick. This indicates that the bears tried to push\r\nthe price down, but the bulls were able to push it back up, suggesting a\r\npossible shift in momentum.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Based on this observation, the trader decides to enter a\r\nlong position on the asset, with a stop-loss set just below the low of the\r\nhammer pattern. The stop-loss is a price level at which the trader will exit\r\nthe trade if the price moves against them, helping to manage risk.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">As the price continues to move up, the trader may decide to\r\nexit the trade when they see a bearish reversal pattern forming, suggesting a\r\npotential trend reversal. A bearish reversal pattern is the opposite of a\r\nbullish reversal pattern and suggests a potential shift from an uptrend to a\r\ndowntrend.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">For example, the trader may notice that the latest\r\ncandlestick on the chart is a \"shooting star\" pattern, which has a\r\nsmall body and a long upper wick, with little to no lower wick. This indicates\r\nthat the bulls tried to push the price up, but the bears were able to push it\r\nback down, suggesting a possible shift in momentum.<o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">Based on this observation, the trader decides to exit their\r\nlong position, taking profits and avoiding potential losses as the trend may be\r\nshifting. They may also consider entering a short position if the bearish\r\nreversal pattern confirms a potential downtrend.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><b>Examples of real-world chart analysis\r\nusing candlestick patterns</b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"margin-left:.5in\"><br></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>', '2023-02-20 05:00:18', '2023-02-21 07:10:21', 1, 'Mastering-Candlestick-Patterns:-A-Comprehensive-Guide-to-Identifying-and-Interpreting-All-Major-Patterns-in-Technical-Analysis', 'aebb7eb20dbea594f0bd29250927928djpeg');

